If a workflow transition chains together 2 or more of the workflow assignment functions *AssignToCurrentUserFunction, AssignToLeadFunction,* or *AssignToReporterFunction*,
then it is possible to get false changes shown in the issue's history.

+To Reproduce+
_The attached *change-history-off.zip* file contains a small set of Jira data that can be restored into a 4.3.4 instance to reproduce this_
# In a workflow have the AssignToCurrentUserFunction follow the AssignToLeadFunction. (The reason for this is that the AssignToCurrentUserFunction will only assign to the current user if they are assignable. So by having the AssignToLeadFunction come before it, then issue will fall back to being assigned to the lead if the current user can't be assigned). See !start progress post functions.png|thumbnail!
# log into jira as a user who has assignment and workflow permission but who isn't the lead of the project. For example, in the data set I've attached, log in as *mickey mouse*. Password is mouse.
# Find or create an issue in Open state
# click Start Progress
# click Stop Progress
# click Start Progress again
# now look at the History issue tab. 

+Expected Result+ the change history shouldn't have a change in assignee listed when we went executed Start Progress the second time. 

+Actual Result+ the change history says that the assignee changed from *mickey hart* to *mickey mouse* even though there wasn't a change in assignment for the second time that we clicked Start Progress. You can tell this is off because the previous Start Progress also shows that the issue was last assigned to *mickey mouse*. See !change history off.png|thumbnail!

+Resolution+
What we have done to fix this on our system (every time we upgrade) is go into the 3 functions and change the issue.setAssignee() call to instead call this function below. (As the comment in the snippet points out it still doesn't work if invoked from SOAP, but that's fairly rare in our system.)

{code}
   /**
    * throw away any intermediate assignee switches made by previous calls to issue.setAssignee()
    * during the chain of workflow functions
    * so that the change history reflects a change from start state to end state
    * for the entire set of workflow functions
    * @param transientVars variables passed between a set of workflow functions
    * @param assignTo new assignee
    */
   protected void setAssignee(Map transientVars, User assignTo) {
      final MutableIssue modifiedIssue = getIssue(transientVars);
      User oldAssignee = modifiedIssue.getAssignee();
      final Object issue = transientVars.get(ORIGINAL_ISSUE_KEY);
      // if we're being invoked from SOAP, then there is no WorkflowFunctionUtils.ORIGINAL_ISSUE_KEY in memory.
      // So just use what the previous set was, which defeats the point of this function.
      // But that's better than a NullPointerException.
      // Otherwise, this next if() statement will pick up the original assignee before all the workflow functions ran and avoid false changes in the change history
      if(issue instanceof Issue) {
         oldAssignee = ((Issue)issue).getAssignee();
      }
      modifiedIssue.setAssignee(assignTo);
      modifiedIssue.store();
      modifiedIssue.getModifiedFields().put(IssueFieldConstants.ASSIGNEE, new ModifiedValue(oldAssignee, assignTo));
   }
{code}

This is something that we noticed years ago...even before 3.13...but for some reason I just keep hacking it and never bothered to ask y'all to fix it. 
If you could fix this, it would be spectacular.

