The user profile section calls back to the plugin implementors via the view layer and typical getHTML() call.

The top level userprofile.jsp has this in it

{code}

<div id="main-content">
    <jsp:include page="viewprofile-tabs.jsp" />
    <div class="active-area">
        <h2 id="up-tab-title"><ww:property value="/labelForSelectedTab"/></h2>
        <jsp:include page="A.jsp" />
    </div>
</div>
{code}

The jsp:include calls makes Tomcat wrap the response object in an ApplicationHttpResponse class.  Why I dont know but it does.

This call WILL NOT allow a bunch of things to be done like adding cookies.

{code}
    /**
     * Disallow <code>addCookie()</code> calls on an included response.
     *
     * @param cookie The new cookie
     */
    public void addCookie(Cookie cookie) {

        if (!included)
            ((HttpServletResponse) getResponse()).addCookie(cookie);

    }

{code}

The code sets that included variable to true in the include() implementation code.  Basically anything that can modify the response headers is disallowed when included.  

This does not happen on other pages because they dont use include(). 

Weird.  This broke Bonfires ability to set error message cookies to avoid using HttpSessions in order to be a good web scale ready client.

